<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>In the AS/AD model, which combination represents stagflation?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Rising prices and rising output</option>
            <option letter="b">Falling prices and falling output</option>
            <option letter="c">Rising prices and falling output</option>
            <option letter="d">Falling prices and rising output</option>
        </options>
        <answer>c</answer>
        <explanation>Stagflation occurs when the economy experiences both inflation (rising prices) and stagnation (falling output), typically caused by negative supply shocks shifting SRAS left.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>If the required reserve ratio is 10% and banks hold no excess reserves, what is the money multiplier?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">0.1</option>
            <option letter="b">1.0</option>
            <option letter="c">10.0</option>
            <option letter="d">100.0</option>
        </options>
        <answer>c</answer>
        <explanation>The money multiplier equals 1/required reserve ratio. With a 10% (0.1) required reserve ratio, the money multiplier is 1/0.1 = 10.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>Which would most likely result from a depreciation of the domestic currency?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Decrease in exports, increase in imports</option>
            <option letter="b">Increase in exports, decrease in imports</option>
            <option letter="c">Increase in both exports and imports</option>
            <option letter="d">Decrease in both exports and imports</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Currency depreciation makes domestic goods cheaper for foreigners (increasing exports) and foreign goods more expensive for domestic buyers (decreasing imports).</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>Which policy would be most appropriate to combat a severe recession?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Increasing interest rates and government spending</option>
            <option letter="b">Decreasing interest rates and taxes</option>
            <option letter="c">Increasing interest rates and taxes</option>
            <option letter="d">Decreasing interest rates and government spending</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>To combat recession, expansionary monetary policy (lower interest rates) and expansionary fiscal policy (lower taxes) would work together to increase aggregate demand.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
